There are four specimens numbered 1269 in MEL, all dated to January 1891; the other specimens are dated 1891 without month or day.

Gahnia (Cladium)
In M to M. Holtze, 8 February 1891, M asks for specimens with ripe fruit, without which identification is impossible.
Note 1 and 3 together suggest that the list ison or before 8 February 1891: these are the only two items in which this record number appears.

p.seg: Zu welcher Sie meine Aufmerksamkeit besonders lenken, ist eine Brassaia. Jedenfalls ist das Genus f√ºr N. W. Austr. neu. Ich will die Art sorgf√§ltig mit den wenigen aus Neu Guinea u den Sunda-Inseln vergleichen, u. sollte sie neu sein, Ihnen widmen.
Die Asclepiadeen sind sehr erw√ºnscht, zumal da Sie auch von diesen Alcohol-Ex. senden.

cell.p:
[To which you particularly draw my attention, is a Brassaia. In any case, the genus is new for N. W. Australia. I will compare the species carefully with the few from New Guinea and the Sunda Islands and should it be new I will dedicate it to you.
These specimens are in MEL under Schefflera actinophylla, treated by APNI as a synonym of Brassaia actonophylla, Endler's name under which M listed it in B89.12.03. IPNI attributes the name to M in B64.06.01 but that is a misinterpretation of the text, which has an extended description but in which it is not claimed as a new species, and M fully cites Endler in B60.11.03, p. 108 when it is mentioned under a discussion of Aralia moorei (Both APNI and IPNI accessed 27 July 2022).
The Asclepiadeae are very desirable, especially as you also send specimens in alcohol.]
